{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WicXK7CkAiDSBTnuDBfhD7","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→description: How to verify different types of acceptance criteria — UI, API, Database, Log. Includes the four-tier verification system and patterns for the verifier subagent and agent-browser usage.\n     3→---\n     4→\n     5→# Verification Patterns\n     6→\n     7→## Verification Tier Guide\n     8→\n     9→Every acceptance criterion is assigned a **verification tier** that determines what evidence is needed to prove it works. The four tiers are:\n    10→\n    11→### `test-provable`\n    12→\n    13→**What it means:** The AC can be verified by building the project, running automated tests, and reading/grepping output or source artifacts.\n    14→\n    15→**Evidence required:** Build output + test results + grep/read of generated files or code.\n    16→\n    17→**No running app. No Docker.**\n    18→\n    19→**Examples:**\n    20→- \"Given a parser function, when called with valid input, then it returns the expected structure\" — run unit tests\n    21→- \"Given the config schema, when validated, then all required fields are present\" — grep config, run tests\n    22→- \"Given a new TypeScript type, when compiled, then no type errors\" — `npm run build` succeeds\n    23→\n    24→**Decision criteria:** Can you prove this AC by running `npm test` or `npm run build` and examining output? If yes, it is `test-provable`.\n    25→\n    26→---\n    27→\n    28→### `runtime-provable`\n    29→\n    30→**What it means:** The AC requires running the actual binary, CLI, or server and interacting with it to verify behavior.\n    31→\n    32→**Evidence required:** Build + run binary/server + interact + check output. No Docker stack needed.\n    33→\n    34→**Examples:**\n    35→- \"Given the CLI is invoked with `--help`, then it prints usage information\" — run the CLI, check stdout\n    36→- \"Given a POST to `/api/items`, then the response is 201 with the created item\" — start server, make HTTP call\n    37→- \"Given the tool processes a file, then it exits with code 0 and produces output\" — run tool, check exit code and output\n    38→\n    39→**Decision criteria:** Do you need to actually run the program (not just tests) to verify? But it works locally without Docker? Then it is `runtime-provable`.\n    40→\n    41→---\n    42→\n    43→### `environment-provable`\n    44→\n    45→**What it means:** The AC requires a full Docker verification environment with `docker exec`, observability queries, or multi-service interaction.\n    46→\n    47→**Evidence required:** `docker exec` commands, observability backend queries (VictoriaLogs, VictoriaMetrics), multi-container orchestration.\n    48→\n    49→**Examples:**\n    50→- \"Given the service is deployed, when a request is made, then logs appear in VictoriaLogs\" — need Docker + observability stack\n    51→- \"Given the worker connects to Redis, when a job is enqueued, then it is processed\" — need Docker Compose with Redis\n    52→- \"Given the full stack is running, when the user completes a workflow, then all services record traces\" — full environment verification\n    53→\n    54→**Decision criteria:** Do you need Docker, external services, or observability infrastructure to verify? Then it is `environment-provable`.\n    55→\n    56→---\n    57→\n    58→### `escalate`\n    59→\n    60→**What it means:** The AC genuinely cannot be verified by automated means. Requires human judgment, physical hardware, or paid third-party services not available in the test environment.\n    61→\n    62→**Evidence required:** Human review. Mark as escalated with justification.\n    63→\n    64→**Examples:**\n    65→- \"Given the email is sent, then it renders correctly in Outlook\" — requires real email client\n    66→- \"Given the payment is processed, then the charge appears on the credit card\" — requires real payment gateway\n    67→- \"Given the hardware sensor is connected, then readings are accurate\" — requires physical device\n    68→\n    69→**Decision criteria:** Have you exhausted all automated approaches? Is there genuinely no way to verify this without a human or external paid service? Only then use `escalate`. This tier is rare.\n    70→\n    71→---\n    72→\n    73→## UI Verification (agent-browser)\n    74→\n    75→Typically `runtime-provable` or `environment-provable` depending on whether the UI requires a Docker stack.\n    76→\n    77→Use agent-browser to interact with the UI like a real user.\n    78→\n    79→### Steps\n    80→1. Navigate to the feature URL\n    81→2. Use accessibility-tree refs to find elements (not CSS selectors)\n    82→3. Interact: click, fill, wait for state changes\n    83→4. Capture annotated screenshots via `showboat image`\n    84→5. Diff before/after states if needed\n    85→\n    86→### Example\n    87→```bash\n    88→# Navigate and screenshot\n    89→showboat exec \"agent-browser navigate http://localhost:3000/feature\"\n    90→showboat image \"Initial state\" --annotate\n    91→\n    92→# Interact\n    93→showboat exec \"agent-browser click 'Submit Button'\"\n    94→showboat exec \"agent-browser wait 'Success Message'\"\n    95→showboat image \"After submission\" --annotate\n    96→```\n    97→\n    98→### Fallback (NFR15)\n    99→If agent-browser is unavailable:\n   100→```\n   101→[WARN] agent-browser unavailable, UI verification skipped\n   102→```\n   103→Note the skip in the proof document. Do NOT fabricate UI evidence.\n   104→\n   105→## API Verification (curl)\n   106→\n   107→Typically `runtime-provable` (local server) or `environment-provable` (Docker-hosted service).\n   108→\n   109→Use real HTTP calls to verify API behavior.\n   110→\n   111→### Steps\n   112→1. Make the API call with curl\n   113→2. Check BOTH status code AND response body\n   114→3. Verify side effects (database state, events emitted)\n   115→\n   116→### Example\n   117→```bash\n   118→# Make API call and capture full response\n   119→showboat exec \"curl -s -w '\\nHTTP_STATUS:%{http_code}' -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/items -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\\\"name\\\":\\\"test\\\"}'\"\n   120→\n   121→# Expected: HTTP_STATUS:201, body contains created item with ID\n   122→```\n   123→\n   124→### What to Check\n   125→- Status code matches expected (201 for create, 200 for get, etc.)\n   126→- Response body contains expected fields\n   127→- Side effects happened (check DB, check logs)\n   128→\n   129→## Database Verification (DB MCP)\n   130→\n   131→Typically `environment-provable` — requires a running database instance.\n   132→\n   133→Use DB MCP for read-only queries to confirm state.\n   134→\n   135→### Steps\n   136→1. Query the database for expected state\n   137→2. Confirm rows exist, values match\n   138→3. Supports PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite (NFR11)\n   139→\n   140→### Example\n   141→```bash\n   142→# Via DB MCP tool\n   143→showboat exec \"SELECT id, name, status FROM items WHERE name = 'test'\"\n   144→# Expected: 1 row with status = 'active'\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→## Log/Trace Verification (VictoriaLogs)\n   148→\n   149→Typically `environment-provable` — requires the observability stack running in Docker.\n   150→\n   151→Query VictoriaLogs to confirm runtime behavior.\n   152→\n   153→### Steps\n   154→1. Query for expected log entries\n   155→2. Confirm trace IDs, event names, or error absence\n   156→\n   157→### Example\n   158→```bash\n   159→# Check for expected log entry\n   160→showboat exec \"curl 'localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_msg:*item created*&start=5m'\"\n   161→# Expected: at least 1 log entry with item creation event\n   162→\n   163→# Confirm no errors\n   164→showboat exec \"curl 'localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=level:error&start=5m'\"\n   165→# Expected: 0 results\n   166→```\n   167→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01K68Y1Foar84i6BFTVSPMJm","session_id":"0e0ced21-c7cd-411a-a5de-15cffee11899","uuid":"8ac45fe8-5d39-4a33-9c65-803db192a78d","timestamp":"2026-03-28T13:05:26.790Z"}
