{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JLeKoKxRy2TgHdXNAzN9Kw","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## WHY\n     2→\n     3→Dev agents repeatedly shipped code without reading module conventions (AGENTS.md),\n     4→skipped observability checks, and produced features that could not be verified\n     5→from outside the source tree. This patch enforces architecture awareness,\n     6→observability validation, documentation hygiene, test coverage gates, and\n     7→verification tier awareness — all operational failures observed in prior sprints.\n     8→(FR33, FR34, NFR20)\n     9→\n    10→## Codeharness Development Enforcement\n    11→\n    12→### Architecture Awareness\n    13→\n    14→Before writing code, read the relevant `AGENTS.md` file for the module being changed. Understand:\n    15→- Build commands and test runners\n    16→- Module boundaries and conventions\n    17→- What NOT to do (common pitfalls documented from prior incidents)\n    18→\n    19→### Observability\n    20→\n    21→Run `semgrep scan --config patches/observability/ --config patches/error-handling/` before committing and fix any gaps.\n    22→\n    23→After running tests, verify telemetry is flowing:\n    24→- Query VictoriaLogs to confirm log events from test runs\n    25→- If observability is configured, traces should be visible for CLI operations\n    26→\n    27→### Documentation\n    28→\n    29→- Update `AGENTS.md` for all changed modules\n    30→- Keep exec-plan current with implementation state\n    31→\n    32→### Testing\n    33→\n    34→- All tests pass before moving to review\n    35→- Coverage gate: 100% of new/changed code\n    36→- Run `npm test` / `pytest` and verify no regressions\n    37→\n    38→### Verification Tier Awareness\n    39→\n    40→Write code that can be verified at the appropriate tier. The four verification tiers determine what evidence is needed to prove an AC works:\n    41→\n    42→- **`test-provable`** — Code must be testable via `npm test` / `npm run build`. Ensure functions have test coverage, outputs are greppable, and build artifacts are inspectable. No running app required.\n    43→- **`runtime-provable`** — Code must be exercisable via CLI or local server. Ensure the binary/CLI produces verifiable stdout, exit codes, or HTTP responses without needing Docker.\n    44→- **`environment-provable`** — Code must work in a Docker verification environment. Ensure the Dockerfile is current, services start correctly, and `docker exec` can exercise the feature. Observability queries should return expected log/trace events.\n    45→- **`escalate`** — Reserved for ACs that genuinely cannot be automated (physical hardware, paid external APIs). This is rare — exhaust all automated approaches first.\n    46→\n    47→Ask yourself:\n    48→- What tier is this story tagged with?\n    49→- Does my implementation produce the evidence that tier requires?\n    50→- If `test-provable`: are my functions testable and my outputs greppable?\n    51→- If `runtime-provable`: can I run the CLI/server and verify output locally?\n    52→- If `environment-provable`: does `docker exec` work? Are logs flowing to the observability stack?\n    53→\n    54→If the answer is \"no\", the feature has a testability gap — fix the code to be verifiable at the appropriate tier.\n    55→\n    56→### Dockerfile Maintenance\n    57→\n    58→If this story adds a new runtime dependency, check whether the Dockerfile needs updating:\n    59→- New system package required at runtime (e.g., `libssl`, `ffmpeg`) — add to `apt-get install` line\n    60→- New binary expected on PATH — add install step to Dockerfile\n    61→- New Python package needed — add to `pip install` or `requirements.txt` COPY\n    62→- Verify the updated Dockerfile still passes `validateDockerfile()` with zero gaps\n    63→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01K68Y1Foar84i6BFTVSPMJm","session_id":"0e0ced21-c7cd-411a-a5de-15cffee11899","uuid":"7c8896f6-f5c2-4631-b150-64806765d106","timestamp":"2026-03-28T13:05:27.005Z"}
